When asked 'how do we version this,' the answer for a single bash file in a git repo is:

  git rev-parse HEAD:mycelium.sh    → blob OID (exact file content)
  git describe --tags --always      → human-readable position in history
  git log -1 --format=%H mycelium.sh → last commit that touched the file

These already existed before we added any versioning code. The SKILL.md
has a blob OID too — git tracks every file's exact content automatically.

What we ADDED:
  - mycelium.sh --version (convenience wrapper around git describe)
  - Installer stamping (for non-git copies)
  - CI version check

What we SHOULD NOT HAVE added (or at least not first):
  - Semver release tags before real-world validation
  - Release engineering infrastructure before we had anything to release

The lesson: git is already a version control system. Use it as one.
Add publishing infrastructure (tags, semver, changelogs) when you
actually have users depending on stable versions. Not before.

For the exploration phase we are in now, git describe is sufficient.
When someone runs mycelium.sh --version and sees v0.2.0-3-gabcdef,
they know exactly what they have. That is version control.
